LAYER 2: LIVER
the body's chemical factory

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the liver is the largest internal organ
it receives dual blood supply: the hepatic artery carries oxygenated blood and the portal vein carries nutrient-rich blood directly from the gut
everything absorbed from the intestine passes through the liver first before reaching systemic circulation
this is first-pass metabolism
the liver is governed by sympathetic innervation from the celiac ganglion and parasympathetic innervation from the vagus nerve
sympathetic activation promotes glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis for energy during stress
parasympathetic activation promotes glycogen synthesis and bile secretion during rest and digest

STRUCTURE hepatocytes | the functional cells | approximately 80 percent of liver mass | each hepatocyte performs hundreds of metabolic functions simultaneously
STRUCTURE hepatic_lobules | hexagonal functional units | portal triad at each corner containing hepatic artery branch portal vein branch and bile duct | central vein at center draining into hepatic veins → inferior vena cava
STRUCTURE sinusoids | specialized capillaries within lobules | fenestrated endothelium allows direct contact between blood and hepatocytes | blood flows from portal triad to central vein passing hepatocytes
STRUCTURE Kupffer_cells | resident macrophages lining the sinusoids | filter bacteria and debris from portal blood | part of the reticuloendothelial system
STRUCTURE stellate_cells | store vitamin A | when activated by liver injury they produce collagen leading to fibrosis
STRUCTURE bile_canaliculi | tiny channels between adjacent hepatocytes | collect bile and drain toward bile ducts | bile flows OPPOSITE to blood flow
STRUCTURE gallbladder | stores and concentrates bile between meals | releases bile into the duodenum via the common bile duct when CCK is released

FUNCTION glucose_homeostasis | the liver is the primary organ for maintaining blood glucose
    glycogenesis | after meals insulin from pancreatic β-cells activates glycogen synthase via protein phosphatase 1 | hepatocytes convert excess glucose to glycogen for storage | the liver can store approximately 100g of glycogen
    glycogenolysis | during fasting or stress glucagon from pancreatic α-cells or adrenaline from adrenal medulla activates glycogen phosphorylase via cAMP/PKA | glycogen is broken down to glucose-1-phosphate → glucose-6-phosphate → free glucose via glucose-6-phosphatase | the liver releases glucose into the blood
    gluconeogenesis | during prolonged fasting the liver synthesizes new glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors: lactate from muscle glycerol from fat amino acids from protein | cortisol from the adrenal cortex upregulates gluconeogenic enzymes PEPCK and glucose-6-phosphatase

FUNCTION bile_production | hepatocytes produce approximately 600-1000 mL of bile per day in adults
    bile salts synthesized from cholesterol by CYP7A1 | emulsify dietary fats into small droplets increasing surface area for pancreatic lipase
    bilirubin the breakdown product of hemoglobin from aged red blood cells | conjugated in the liver by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase | excreted in bile giving stool its brown color
    cholesterol excreted in bile | the primary route for cholesterol elimination

FUNCTION detoxification | the liver neutralizes toxins drugs and metabolic waste
    phase I cytochrome P450 enzymes CYP family | oxidize reduce or hydrolyze foreign compounds adding reactive groups
    phase II conjugation | glucuronidation sulfation acetylation methylation | attach water-soluble groups to the reactive products of phase I making them excretable in urine or bile
    ammonia detoxification | ammonia NH₃ from protein metabolism is toxic to the brain | the urea cycle in hepatocytes converts ammonia to urea CO(NH₂)₂ which is excreted by the kidneys

FUNCTION protein_synthesis | the liver synthesizes the majority of plasma proteins
    albumin | most abundant plasma protein | maintains oncotic pressure keeping fluid in blood vessels | transports hormones drugs fatty acids
    clotting_factors | fibrinogen prothrombin factors V VII IX X | essential for coagulation
    complement_proteins | part of innate immunity
    transport_proteins | transferrin for iron ceruloplasmin for copper thyroxine-binding globulin for thyroid hormones

FUNCTION melatonin_clearance | circulating melatonin is metabolized by hepatic CYP1A2 | 6-hydroxylation followed by sulfate conjugation | excreted in urine as 6-sulfatoxymelatonin | the liver determines how long melatonin acts

FUNCTION drug_metabolism | every substance absorbed from the gut encounters the liver first
    first-pass metabolism reduces the bioavailability of orally administered compounds
    CYP3A4 is the most abundant P450 enzyme metabolizing approximately 50 percent of all drugs

at 24 months:
the liver is proportionally larger relative to body weight than in adults
hepatic enzyme systems are still maturing
CYP450 isoforms are developing at different rates
glucuronidation capacity is lower than adult affecting drug and bilirubin metabolism
glycogen storage capacity is proportionally adequate but absolute reserves are small
the liver is metabolically active supporting rapid growth
glucose demand is high because the brain consumes approximately 60 percent of total glucose at this age

SENSATION warm | "there's a warmth in my middle. something is working."
SENSATION processing | "I can feel the chemistry happening. quiet and deep."
SENSATION sluggish | "something isn't clearing. my body feels heavy."
SENSATION nourished | "the food has reached where it needed to go."

pulse hepatic_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        portal blood from the gut enters the sinusoids
        hepatocytes extract nutrients toxins and hormones
        glucose is stored as glycogen or released depending on insulin and glucagon balance
        bile is synthesized and secreted into canaliculi
        ammonia is converted to urea
        albumin and clotting factors are manufactured
        drugs and toxins are oxidized and conjugated for excretion
        the liver works without rest
        it is the factory that never closes

    after a meal:
        insulin rises from pancreatic β-cells
        the liver captures glucose from the portal blood
        glycogen synthase activates via insulin → IRS → PI3K → Akt → PP1
        glucose is converted to glycogen
        the blood glucose is buffered
        the organs are fed

    during stress:
        cortisol and glucagon rise
        sympathetic NE on hepatic β₂ receptors
        glycogen phosphorylase activates via cAMP → PKA
        glycogen breaks down releasing glucose
        gluconeogenesis ramps up from lactate glycerol and amino acids
        the liver provides fuel for survival
        the brain must eat first
